# git-rebase-signing-ci — History

## v1.1.0 (2026-07-12)

**Changed by:** Hephaestus PR #2099 (branch `2053-auto-impl`) — rebasing a
1-commit PR branch onto ~38 new commits of `origin/main`, hit one real
content conflict in `docs/AUTOMATION_LOOP_ARCHITECTURE.md`, then hand-invoked
the queued `--exec` command after resolving the conflict instead of running
`git rebase --continue`.

**Verification:** verified-local

### What changed

- Added a critical warning to the Verified Workflow: never hand-invoke the
  `--exec` command after resolving a conflict — always run
  `git rebase --continue` first, since the conflicted commit has not yet been
  finalized as a real commit object at that pause point.
- Added a new Failed Attempts row documenting the corrupted-commit failure
  mode (amend lands on the rebase's "onto" checkout instead of the picked
  commit, silently merging in an unrelated upstream commit's diff and
  message).
- Added a recovery procedure using `git reset --keep <pre-rebase-sha>` +
  `git rebase --quit` for repos where `git rebase --abort` is blocked by a
  safety-net policy.
- Added a "redo without `--exec`" pattern: plain `git rebase origin/main`,
  resolve conflicts, `git rebase --continue` to completion, THEN a single
  standalone `git commit --amend --no-edit -s -S` pass over the final HEAD —
  decoupling conflict-resolution-continuation from the signing amend.

### Why

The v1.0.0 Quick Reference recommended
`git rebase --exec 'git commit --amend --no-edit -S' origin/main` without
warning about what happens if a pick in the middle of that rebase conflicts.
A conflict forces the operator to intervene, and the natural (but wrong)
instinct is to manually replicate the queued `--exec` command since the
rebase reports "Next command to do: exec ...". At that point, though,
`git rebase` is still mid-`pick` — the conflicted commit doesn't exist yet as
a commit object, and running `git commit --amend` amends whatever HEAD
currently is (the "onto" checkout, i.e. the base branch tip), not the
in-progress pick. This produced a corrupted commit whose diff was the union
of an unrelated upstream commit's changes plus the PR's own changes, under
the wrong commit message/title. Diagnosed via `git reflog` showing no
intervening pick entry between the rebase-start checkout and the amend.

